{"questionId":"22596242","questionHtml":"<p>Consider <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup></math>.</p>\n<p>Find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math> such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math> satisfy the above two equations.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;(seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempts to find an expression for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup></mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;(as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup><mo>≠</mo><mn>0</mn></math>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempts to integrate their&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>∫</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A0</strong></em> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced></msup></math> (or equivalent expressed with an arbitrary constant).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22596242","referenceCode":"24M.3.AHL.TZ2.1d","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Consider gx=xex. Find fx such that fx and gx satisfy the above two equations.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.16—Integration by substitution, parts and repeated parts"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}